codelist.label: Event Process
codelist.definition: Terms specifying the process or processes that occurred during an event.

extensibility.label: Extensible with values at any level

value.label: bolide impact
value.definition: The impact of an extraterrestrial body on the surface of the earth.

value.label: deep water oxygen depletion
value.definition: Process of removal of oxygen from from the deep part of a body of water.

value.label: deformation
value.definition: Movement of rock bodies by displacement on fault or shear zones, or change in shape of a body of earth material.

value.label: diagenetic process
value.definition: Any chemical, physical, or biological process that affects a sedimentary earth material after initial deposition, and during or after lithification, exclusive of weathering and metamorphism.

value.label: extinction
value.definition: Process of disappearance of a species or higher taxon, so that it no longer exists anywhere or in the subsequent fossil record.

value.label: geomagnetic process
value.definition: Process that results in change in Earth's magnetic field.

value.label: human activity
value.definition: Processes of human modification of the earth to produce geologic features.

value.label: magmatic process
value.definition: A process involving melted rock (magma).

value.label: metamorphic process
value.definition: Mineralogical, chemical, and structural adjustment of solid rocks to physical and chemical conditions that differ from the conditions under which the rocks in question originated, and are generally been imposed at depth, below the surface zones of weathering and cementation.

value.label: sea level change
value.definition: Process of mean sea level changing relative to some datum.

value.label: sedimentary process
value.definition: A phenomenon that changes the distribution or physical properties of sediment at or near the earth's surface.

value.label: speciation
value.definition: Process that results inappearance of new species.

value.label: tectonic process
value.definition: Processes related to the interaction between or deformation of rigid plates forming the crust of the Earth.

value.label: weathering
value.definition: The process or group of processes by which earth materials exposed to atmospheric agents at or near the Earth's surface are changed in color, texture, composition, firmness, or form, with little or no transport of the loosened or altered material. Processes typically include oxidation, hydration, and leaching of soluble constituents.

value.label: accretion
value.definition: The addition of material to a continent. Typically involves convergent or transform motion.

value.label: alteration
value.definition: General term for any change in the mineralogical or chemical composition of a rock. Typically related to interaction with hydrous fluids.

value.label: biological precipitation
value.definition: the deposition of minerals from solution by the agency of organisms

value.label: biological weathering
value.definition: breakdown of rocks by biological agents, e.g. the penetrating and expanding force of roots, the presence of moss and lichen causing humic acids to be retained in contact with rock, and the work of animals (worms, moles, rabbits) in modifying surface soil

value.label: casting
value.definition: covering of the surface with a material liquid during processing and solidifying afterwards

value.label: chemical precipitation
value.definition: The deposition of mineral matter by precipitation from solution or as a result of chemical reactions. May be sedimentary or hydrothermal.

value.label: chemical weathering
value.definition: The process of weathering by which chemical reactions (hydrolysis, hydration, oxidation, carbonation, ion exchange, and solution) transform rocks and minerals into new chemical combinations that are stable under conditions prevailing at or near the Earth's surface; e.g. the alteration of orthoclase to kaolinite.

value.label: cometary impact
value.definition: the impact of a comet on the surface of the earth

value.label: contact metamorphism
value.definition: Metamorphism taking place in rocks at or near their contact with a genetically related body of igneous rock

value.label: continental breakup
value.definition: Fragmentation of a continental plate into two or more smaller plates; may involve rifting or strike slip faulting.

value.label: continental collision
value.definition: The amalgamation of two continental plates or blocks along a convergent margin.

value.label: cryoturbation
value.definition: A collective term to describe the stirring and churning of unconsolidated material resulting from frost action

value.label: debris flow deposition
value.definition: Laminar high-concentration, generally cohesionless deposition process. Flow types included liquefied flow, fluidized flow, grain flow, traction carpet or modified grain flow.

value.label: deep ploughing
value.definition: mixing of loose surface material by ploughing deeper than frequently done during annual soil cultivation

value.label: deformation twinning
value.definition: Deformation of a crystal by gliding to produce crystallographic twinning.

value.label: deluviation
value.definition: process of non-linear, grain-size selective erosion

value.label: deposition
value.definition: Accumulation of material; the constructive process of accumulation of sedimentary particles, chemical precipitation of mineral matter from solution, or the accumulation of organicMaterial on the death of plants and animals.

value.label: deposition by or from moving ice
value.definition: Deposition of sediment from ice by melting or pushing. The material has been transported in the ice after entrainment in the moving ice or after deposition from other moving fluids on the ice.

value.label: deposition from air
value.definition: Deposition of sediment from air, in which the sediment has been transported after entrainment in the moving air.

value.label: deposition from fluid
value.definition: Deposition of sediment from moving water or air, in which the sediment is transported by entrainment in the moving fluid. Constrast with debris flow or turbidity current deposition in which movement of fluid/sediment mixture is due to incorporation of sediment in fluid.

value.label: deposition from moving fluid
value.definition: Deposition of sediment from moving water or air, in which the sediment is transported by entrainment in the moving fluid. Constrast with debris flow or turbidity current deposition in which movement of fluid/sediment mixture is due to incorporation of sediment in fluid.

value.label: deposition from water
value.definition: Deposition of sediment from water, in which the sediment has been transported after entrainment in the moving water or after deposition from other moving fluids.

value.label: diffusion creep
value.definition: Grain-scale, ductile deformation accomplished by the motion of atoms through crystals, along grain boundaries, and through pore fluids.

value.label: digging
value.definition: repeated mixing of loose surface material by digging with a spade or similar tool

value.label: dislocation metamorphism
value.definition: Metamorphism concentrated along narrow belts of shearing or crushing without an appreciable rise in temperature

value.label: dissolution
value.definition: The process of dissolving into a homogenous solution, as when an acidic solution dissolves limestone. In karst, refers to the process of dissolving rock to produce landforms, in contrast to solution, the chemical product of dissolution.

value.label: dissolution creep
value.definition: Deformation by dissolution under the effects of differential stress and its transport to a new location by movement of fluid in the rock body.

value.label: ductile flow
value.definition: deformation without apparent loss of continuity at the scale of observation.

value.label: dumping
value.definition: heaping of mostly solid material, as in a land fill, mine dump, dredging operations

value.label: effusive eruption
value.definition: Eruptions characterized by low volatile content of the erupting magma relative to ambient pressure

value.label: erosion
value.definition: The process of disaggregation of rock and displacement of the resultant particles (sediment) usually by the agents of currents such as, wind, water, or ice by downward or down-slope movement in response to gravity or by living organisms (in the case of bioerosion).

value.label: eruption
value.definition: The ejection of volcanic materials (lava, pyroclasts, and volcanic gases) onto the Earth's surface, either from a central vent or from a fissure or group of fissures

value.label: excavation
value.definition: removal of material, as in a mining operation

value.label: faulting
value.definition: The process of fracturing, frictional slip, and displacement accumulation that produces a fault

value.label: folding
value.definition: deformation in which planar surfaces become regularly curviplanar surfaces with definable limbs (zones of lower curvature) and hinges (zones of higher curvature).

value.label: fracturing
value.definition: The formation of a surface of failure resulting from stress

value.label: frost shattering
value.definition: Propagation of fractures due to expansion of freezing water in intergranular spaces and fractures in a rock body. Result is mechanical disintegration spliitting, or breakup of rock.

value.label: geologic process
value.definition: process that effects the geologic record

value.label: grading
value.definition: leveling of earth surface by rearrangement of prexisting material

value.label: haloclasty
value.definition: propagation of fractures in rock due to crytallization of mineral salts (typically sodium chloride) from interstitial water, or volumetrick expansion of salts in capillaries, or hydration pressure of interstitial, trapped salts. Generally results in mechanical disintegration of the rock surface.

value.label: hawaiian eruption
value.definition: Eruption in which great quantities of extremely fluid basaltic lava are poured out, mainly issuing in lava fountains from fissures on the flanks of a volcano. Explosive phenomena are rare, but much spatter and scoria are piled into cones and mounds along the vents. Characteristic of shield volcanoes

value.label: hydration
value.definition: The process of absorption of water into the crystal structure of a mineral, thereby changing its volume and fracturing and loosening grains

value.label: hydrolysis
value.definition: A decomposition reaction involving water. In geology, it commonly indicates reaction between silicate minerals and either pure water or aqueous solution. In such reactions, H

value.label: ice erosion
value.definition: Erosion by corrasion or plucking by moving ice.

value.label: in-situ organismic growth
value.definition: accumulation of dead organicMaterial originating from the plants, e.g. peat accumulation in bogs

value.label: intrusion
value.definition: The process of emplacement of magma in pre-existing rock

value.label: magmatic crystallisation
value.definition: The process by which matter becomes crystalline, from a gaseous, fluid, or dispersed state

value.label: magnetic field reversal
value.definition: geomagnetic event

value.label: mass wasting
value.definition: the dislodgement and downslope transport of soil and rock material under the direct application of gravitational body stresses. In contrast to other erosion processes, the debris removed by mass wasting is not carried within, on, or under another medium. The mass properties of the material being transported depend on the interaction of the soil and rock particles and on the moisture content.

value.label: mass wasting deposition
value.definition: A general term for the dislodgement and downslope transport of soil and rock material under the direct application of gravitational body stresses. In contrast to other erosion processes, the debris removed by mass wasting is not carried within, on, or under another medium. The mass properties of the material being transported depend on the interaction of the soil and rock particles and on the moisture content. Mass wasting includes slow displacements, such as creep and solifluction, and rapid movements such as rockfalls, rockslides, and cohesive debris flows (Jackson, 1997, p. 392). Includes both subaerial mass-wasting processes and subaqueous mass-wasting processes.

value.label: material transport and deposition
value.definition: transport and heaping of material, as in a land fill, mine dump, dredging operations

value.label: mechanical deposition
value.definition: process by which material that is being transported as particles by moving air, water, ice, or other fluid comes to rest and accumulates.

value.label: melting
value.definition: change of state from a solid to a liquid

value.label: meteorite impact
value.definition: the impact of a meteorite on the surface of the earth

value.label: microfracturing
value.definition: Development of fractures within a single grain or cutting several grains.

value.label: mixing
value.definition: Mixing

value.label: obduction
value.definition: The overthrusting of continental crust by oceanic crust or mantle rocks at a convergent plate boundary.

value.label: organic accumulation
value.definition: sediment accumulation of biologically produced organicMaterial, as in bog, coal swamps.

value.label: orogenic process
value.definition: mountain building process.

value.label: oxidation
value.definition: Chemical reaction that involve stripping of electrons from cations. Typicall reactions include converting sulfide minerals to oxide minerals, or increasing the oxidation state of cations in existing oxide minerals. The most commonly observed is the oxidation of Fe

value.label: partial melting
value.definition: Process of melting involving only some of the mineral phases in a rock, to produce a mixture of melt and residual particles.

value.label: physical weathering
value.definition: The process of weathering by which frost action, salt-crystal growth, absorption of water, and other physical processes break down a rock to fragments, involving no chemical change

value.label: plinian eruption
value.definition: An explosive eruption in which a steady, turbulent stream of fragmented magma and magmatic gas is released at a high velocity from a vent. Large volumes of tephra and tall eruption columns are characteristic

value.label: polar wander
value.definition: process of migration of the axis of the earth's dipole field relative to the rotation axis of the Earth.

value.label: pressure release weathering
value.definition: propagation of fractures near the surface of solid rock due to expansion related to release of confining pressure when deeply buried rock is unroofed. Fractures typically propagate along surfaces close to and subparallel to the surface of the outcrop.

value.label: pyroclastic eruption
value.definition: Eruption produced by the generation and rapid expansion of a gas phase that disrupts magma, surrounding wall rock or sediment

value.label: reworking
value.definition: near-range transport by water with predominantly changing the inner physical organisation of the sediment particles

value.label: rifting
value.definition: Extension of the crust to form one or more long, narrow graben of regional extent.

value.label: sea level fall
value.definition: process of mean sea level falling relative to some datum

value.label: sea level rise
value.definition: process of mean sea level rising relative to some datum

value.label: sealing
value.definition: covering of the surface with a non-liquid material not or little permeable for water after processing

value.label: shearing
value.definition: A deformation in which contiguous parts of a body are displaced relatively to each other in a direction parallel to a surface. The surface may be a discrete fault, or the deformation may be a penetrative strain and the shear surface is a geometric abstraction.

value.label: spreading
value.definition: A process whereby new oceanic crust is formed by upwelling of magma at the center of mid-ocean ridges and by a moving-away of the new material from the site of upwelling at rates of one to ten centimeters per year.

value.label: strombolian eruption
value.definition: Eruption characterized by jetting of clots or fountains of fluid, basaltic lava from a central crater

value.label: subduction
value.definition: The process of one lithospheric plate descending beneath another

value.label: thermal shock weathering
value.definition: propagation of fractures near the surface of solid rock due to expansion and contraction caused by temperature changes. Fractures typically propagate along surfaces close to and subparallel to the surface of the outcrop.

value.label: transform faulting
value.definition: A strike-slip fault that links two other faults or two other plate boundaries (e.g. two segments of a mid-ocean ridge). Transform faults often exhibit characteristics that distinguish them from transcurrent faults: (1) For transform faults formed at the same time as the faults they link, slip on the transform fault has equal magnitude at all points along the transform; slip magnitude on the transform fault can exceed the length of the transform fault, and slip does not decrease to zero at the fault termini. (2) For transform faults linking two similar features, e.g. if two mid-ocean ridge segments linked by a transform have equal spreading rates, then the length of the transform does not change as slip accrues on it.

value.label: turbidity current deposition
value.definition: Deposition from a turbulent, low concentration sediment-water mixture.

value.label: vulcanian eruption
value.definition: Eruption characterized by the explosive ejection of fragments of new lava, commonly incandescent when they leave the vent but either solid or too viscous to assume any appreciable degree of rounding during their flight through the air. With these there are often breadcrust bombs or blocks, and generally large proportions of ash

value.label: water erosion
value.definition: Erosion by clast impact or plucking by moving liquid water

value.label: wind erosion
value.definition: Erosion by clast impact or plucking by moving air (wind)
